To assess safety, a crash analysis was conducted along the SR 144 corridor from SR 119 to the I‐95
interchange. A crash analysis was also conducted at the US 84 intersection of Old Sunbury Road and Old
Hines Road, locally known as the “US 84 Curve”. Figure 2 on the following page depicts the safety
analysis locations: the SR 144 Corridor and US 84 Curve. The crash analysis for the corridor included the
Long Form reported crashes obtained by GDOT from local sheriff’s and police departments and state
highway patrol. Crash records and summary reports from the military police were collected for locations
within the Fort Stewart boundary and local authorities were used to collect crash records and summary
reports for areas outside of the Fort Stewart boundary. While the original crash report sources were the
local law enforcement, state highway patrol, and Fort Stewart, summary crash data were obtained from
the Liberty Consolidated Planning Commission for years 2007 through 2010. It should be noted that the
crash data for December of 2010 were not available at the time of this report; therefore, the crash
analysis duration was 3.92 years. Because comparing crash data by individual years may distort analysis
results, three years of data were analyzed to account for anomalies caused by outside influence such as
construction projects. All crashes resulting in a vehicle being towed away, personal injury, or fatality are
documented on Long Form crash reports. Recommendations to reduce the crash frequency are
provided at the end of this section.

text.b: A. SR 144 from SR 119 to I­95

page.text: The SR 144 corridor is a 2‐lane highway that connects I‐95 to Fort Stewart, Georgia. The roadway has a
speed limit of 55 miles per hour (mph) for civilian traffic and 40 mph for tactical vehicles. SR 144 in this
section is generally flat with roadside drainage conveyance consisting of grass swales. The roadside
swales on the east end of the corridor appear to have slopes greater than 3:1, which would normally
necessitate a guard rail or modification of the slope to 3:1 or flatter.
Crash records from 2007 through 2010 were collected and summarized for the SR 144 corridor and can
be found in Appendix A of this report. Crash types recorded were mostly animal strikes and run off the
road crashes. The roadway does have rumble strips installed on the shoulders of the road to alert
motorists that they are departing the travel lanes. The SR 144 corridor experiences a high amount of
military tactical training vehicles as the roadway is located on an easement within the boundaries of the
military installation. Signage along the corridor is present to alert motorists of tactical vehicle crossings
at several locations over the 20 mile segment. Based on the crash data, collisions between motorists
and tactical vehicles did not appear to be a safety issue for this study.
From 2007 through 2010, 205 recorded crashes along the SR 144 corridor. Fort Stewart reported 204 of
the crashes and the Richmond Hill Police Department reported one crash during that time frame. The
majority of the crashes occurred during the work week, Monday through Friday, as this route is used
mainly as a commuter route for employees of the Fort Stewart military installation. The traffic patterns
show a high demand from Monday through Friday and as depicted in Table 1, 177 crashes (86%)

The corridor assessment methodology includes the assignment of a level of service (LOS) similar to that
of a letter grade. LOS is a quantitative stratification of quality of service separated into six letter grade
levels, A through F, with LOS A representing the best operating conditions and LOS F the worst. LOS
provides a planning and preliminary engineering technique to address multimodal service inside the
roadway environment (essentially inside the right‐of‐way). Capacity conceptually relates to the
maximum number of vehicles or persons that can pass a point on a roadway in a given amount of time

page.text: The SR 144 corridor study begins at the interchange of Interstate 95 (I‐95) and SR 144 and terminates at

but it is constructed on an easement provided by the Fort Stewart Military Installation. The roadway is a
two‐lane highway with a posted speed limit of 55 mph for civilian vehicles. The AM peak hour was
determined to be the critical time period and due to the lack of tactical vehicles present in the AM peak
period, only non‐tactical traffic was used for this corridor analysis.
The 2010 “Before” AADT for this segment is 8,645 vehicles. Based on the relocation of the IBCT, the SR
144 corridor is expected to experience a growth of 15% east of MR 47 and a growth of 36% between MR
47 and SR 119 as the entrance to the IBCT is located off of SR 144 in this segment. The forecasted AADT
east of MR 47 is 9,950 vehicles and 14,090 vehicles between MR 47 and SR 119.
The traffic characteristics of SR 144 between I‐95 and MR 47 suggest that during the peak hours, the
route is primarily used for Fort Stewart Installation employees. During the AM peak hour, 89% of the

moving away from the Installation. The “Before” and “After” HCS+ results (using the Two‐Way Two‐

Short‐term and Long‐term solutions have been indentified to alleviate congestion and provide a safe
roadway network for the troops of Fort Stewart and the motorists in and around the Hinesville /
Flemington area. It is recommended that the low‐cost solutions be implemented prior to the relocation
of the IBCT. Activities such as restriping and speed enforcement can be implemented almost
immediately and could help to reduce crashes throughout the area. Areas of further study have been
identified and are explained in detail in the following section. Key action items for study partners
include the following, many of which are underway:
Region/Fort Stewart pursue defense access funds for improvements
Region pursue TSPLOST funds for Flemington Loop to bypass US 84 curve
HAMPO continue to plan for and program MPO funds
HAMPO pursue GDOT funds (e.g., safety) for US 84 curve improvements
County/HAMPO/GDOT complete maintenance, restriping, and signage at Old Sunbury Road/US
Flemington pursue scenic byway designation for Old Sunbury Road
The Fort Stewart Traffic Study was completed in twelve weeks beginning in late 2010. The focus was on
near term impacts of the relocation of the 4
IBCT and solutions that can be implemented within a short
time period either prior to summer 2011, or soon thereafter. The study team recognizes that there are
longer term issues which will require further study to ensure the safe and efficient movement of people
in goods in the study area. Specific recommendations for further study include the following:
1. Commercial Vehicle Gate designation Impact Analysis (prior to any change from Gate 7 to Gate
5 or a new gate north of the cantonment area)
2. I‐95 at SR 144 intersection capacity analysis (Interchange Modification Report)
3. True “After” study once IBCT has relocated and troops are back from deployment.
